  "prompt": "\"We think your work speaks for itself, so there's no need to write a cover letter.\" Is this a test from Google interviewers? Should I write a cover letter?",
  "response": "When a company like Google says \"no need for a cover letter,\" it's usually genuine, not a hidden test. Here's some advice:\n\n1. Follow their instructions precisely\n- If they specifically say no cover letter, don't submit one\n- They receive thousands of applications and want a streamlined process\n\n2. Let your resume and application do the talking\n- Google wants to see clear, concise professional achievements\n- Your resume should highlight impact, metrics, and relevant skills\n\n3. Alternative ways to stand out\n- Make your resume extremely clear and compelling\n- If given an opportunity to add additional information, be strategic\n- Prepare a strong narrative for interviews about your background\n\n4. There are some exceptions\n- If you have a unique career transition or significant context\n- If you have a personal connection or referral\n- In these cases, a brief, targeted note might be appropriate\n\n5. Google's typical process\n- They focus more on technical skills, problem-solving, and interviews\n- Your coding/technical portfolio often matters more than a cover letter\n\nPro tip: If uncertain, you can briefly ask their recruiting team for clarification about supplemental materials.\n\nRemember: Always prioritize following the specific application instructions for each company.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
